an Civil War","branch":"Union Army","rank":"Private","unit":"Co. E, then Co. C (consolidated), 4th Illinois Cavalry","war_id":"WAR006","notes":"enlisted 1862; mustered out Memphis, June 15, 1865"}],"narrative_blocks":[{"number":1,"category":"military","header":"Mustered out, he never reached home","body":"Discharged at Memphis in June 1865, the 4th Illinois cavalryman made it as far as a friend’s house in Granville, Illinois, where chronic dysentery from the service killed him on July 1 — days after writing his wife, “I am glad my country is so near free. Hope I shall soon enjoy such freedom.”"},{"number":2,"category":"death","header":"They opened the grave at sunset","body":"His telegram-delayed wife arrived two days after the burial; that Monday evening, after sundown, friends raised the coffin so she could look once more on his face. A thousand people had attended the funeral — and one near relative."},{"number":3,"category":"death","header":"He never saw his youngest child","body":"Three years a soldier, he died with “the intense desire to see his family, especially the youngest, upon whom his eyes never rested.” A son of temperance, he kept his pledge inviolate, even in the army."}],"slug":"lorenzo-cornelius-lory-davis-x03344"},"HD6361":{"id":"HD6361","bio":{"display_name":"Mary M. Leavitt Davis Hillman","gender":"female","bio_blurb":"Twice-widowed keeper of Lory’s letters"},"classification":{"include_in_path_calculation":false,"generation_from_thomas":8,"descent_from_thomas_hooker":true,"descent_from_john_talcott":false,"is_thomas_descendant":true,"is_talcott_descendant":false,"is_easter_egg":false},"has_descendants_documented":true,"number_of_marriages":2,"tags":[],"sources":[],"birth":{"year":1833,"month":3,"day":11,"city":"Heath","state":"Massachusetts"},"death":{"year":1915,"month":6,"state":"New York"},"marriages":[{"marriage_number":1,"spouse_id":"X03344","date_year":1854,"children_ids":["HD6373","HD6374","HD6375","HD6376"]},{"marriage_number":2,"spouse_